Individualised and dynamic representations of text data (Veni presentation)

Bennett Kleinberg

14 February, 2021

Text as data!?

  • Text is everywhere. And everything is text.
  • text as data (Gentzkow, Kelly, and Taddy 2019; Salganik 2019) as a new lens on human behaviour
  • long-standing issue of qualitative experiences vs.quantitative methods

But things have changed

Untapped potential

  • key advances in compuational research attributable to Natural Language Processing (NLP)
  • paradigm shift in NLP: fully statistical approach to language (Manning and Schtze 1999)
  • allowed the quantitative modelling of semantic representations (Garg et al. 2018; Mikolov et al. 2013; Pennington, Socher, and Manning 2014)

But: this assumes that language representations are static and generic

Missing pieces

  • granularity to examine within-person processes over time
  • interpretability to understand changes
  • data efficiency to work with reasonably-sized data that can be expected from individuals (e.g., series of posts/diary).

Project objectives

  1. advancing the methods from statistical NLP to individual-level and longitudinal data
  2. understanding how changes in language representation correspond to and predict changes in psychological variables

Goal: narrowing the gap in our fundamental understanding of text data for social science research

The DILAR method

  • Dynamic (D) -
  • Individualised (I) -
  • Language (LA) -
  • Representations (R) -

Change quantification and detection

  • networks
  • embeddings
  • BAIL Bringmann

Project phases

  1. method development in a semi-observational design
    • historical, longitudinal data from Reddit
    • obtained with consent from participants
  2. experience sampling in diary study

New understanding

So what?

social science/psychology view

  • meaning/concepts change
  • and differ between individuals
  • no use for data-hungry approaches
  • big promise:
  • enter DILAR
